	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;CovariateVariable">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&bfo;STATO_0000258"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">covariate variable</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Incubation temperature or dissolved oxygen concentration, when recorded but not deliberately altered, used to quantify environmental variability</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBCS_0000040</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>CovariateVariable(x) → Variable(x)</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
		<iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="&xsd;boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">variable that is monitored rather than assigned and whose observed values are included in statistical analysis to represent sources of variation in the dependent variable so that their effects can be estimated and separated from those of the factors under study</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
		<iof-av:primitiveRationale>There are insufficient constructs to create a set of necessary and sufficient conditions.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
		<iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>if x is a &apos;covariate variable&apos; then x is a &apos;variable&apos;</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;DataPreparationProcess">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&bfo;OBI_0200000"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&iof-construct;hasSpecifiedOutput"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<owl:Class>
								<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
									<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;IAO_0000027">
									</rdf:Description>
									<owl:Restriction>
										<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&iof-construct;isInputOf"/>
										<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="&iof-construct;PlannedProcess"/>
									</owl:Restriction>
								</owl:intersectionOf>
							</owl:Class>
							<owl:Class>
								<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
									<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;IAO_0000027">
									</rdf:Description>
									<owl:Restriction>
										<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&iof-construct;satisfiesRequirement"/>
										<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="&iof-construct;RequirementSpecification"/>
									</owl:Restriction>
								</owl:intersectionOf>
							</owl:Class>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:someValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">data preparation process</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>removing duplicate entries, converting measurement units, imputing missing values, or merging datasets to create an analysis-ready table; filtering data to retain relevant observations for downstream analysis; encoding categorical variables as numerical values to enable statistical modeling; removing outliers or influential points identified through preliminary analysis to improve model robustness; transforming skewed variables using logarithmic or power transformations to stabilize variance; standardizing or normalizing features to enable comparison across scales in multivariate analysis</skos:example>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Data preparation involves applying one or more data transformations to convert raw or heterogeneous data into a consistent, usable form. It typically includes steps such as handling missing values, correcting errors, standardizing formats, or restructuring data for analysis, integration, or reporting.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>DataPreparationProcess(x) → DataTransformation(x) ∧ ∃a (hasSpecifiedOutput(x, a) ∧ DataItem(a) ∧ ((∃b (isInputOf(a, b) ∧ PlannedProcess(b))) ∨ (∃c (satisfiesRequirement(a, c) ∧ RequirementSpecification(c)))))</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
		<iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="&xsd;boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">data transformation process in which input data are cleaned, organized, or otherwise modified to make them suitable for subsequent analysis or use</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
		<iof-av:primitiveRationale>There are insufficient constructs to create a set of necessary and sufficient conditions.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
		<iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>if x is a &apos;data preparation process&apos; then x is a &apos;data transformation&apos; and x &apos;has specified output&apos; some &apos;data item&apos; that either &apos;is input of&apos; some &apos;planned process&apos; or &apos;satisfies requirement&apos; some &apos;requirement specification&apos;</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;ExplainedVariance">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&bfo;STATO_0000039"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">explained variance</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>coefficient of determination that represents the variance explained by a linear model; eta-squared that represents the variance explained in an ANOVA analysis</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://www.statology.org/explained-variance/ and http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000564</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>ExplainedVariance(x) → Statistic(x)</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
		<iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="&xsd;boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">statistic representing the portion of the total variance in a dependent variable that is attributable to one or more independent variables within a model</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
		<iof-av:primitiveRationale>There are insufficient constructs to create a set of necessary and sufficient conditions.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
		<iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>if x is an &apos;explained variance&apos; then x is a &apos;statistic&apos;</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;ExploratoryDataAnalysis">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;PlannedProcess"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">exploratory data analysis</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>computing summary statistics such as mean, variance, or correlation coefficients; plotting histograms, boxplots, or scatter matrices to visualize data distributions and relationships; identifying missing values or outliers in experimental results before modeling</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/en/#iso:std:iso-iec:22989:ed-1:v1:en:term:3.2.6 and https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/exploratory-data-analysis</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Exploratory Data Analysis involves determining and describing features of a dataset or its subsets through summary statistics, visualization, and other descriptive techniques. It supports understanding of data structure, relationships, outliers, and quality before applying formal modeling or hypothesis testing.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>ExploratoryDataAnalysis(x) → PlannedProcess(x)</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
		<iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="&xsd;boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">planned process used to determine and analyze characteristics of a dataset or its parts in order to identify structure, trends, or irregularities</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
		<iof-av:primitiveRationale>There are insufficient constructs to create a set of necessary and sufficient conditions.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
		<iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>if x is an &apos;exploratory data analysis&apos; then x is a &apos;planned process&apos;</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;ImpactInformationContentEntity">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;InformationContentEntity"/>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&iof-construct;specifiesImpactSource"/>
				<owl:allValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;BFO_0000008">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;BFO_0000020">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;BFO_0000144">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="&iof-construct;ProcessCharacteristic">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:allValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&iof-construct;specifiesImpactTarget"/>
				<owl:allValuesFrom>
					<owl:Class>
						<owl:unionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;BFO_0000008">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;BFO_0000020">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;BFO_0000144">
							</rdf:Description>
							<rdf:Description rdf:about="&iof-construct;ProcessCharacteristic">
							</rdf:Description>
						</owl:unionOf>
					</owl:Class>
				</owl:allValuesFrom>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:subClassOf>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&iof-construct;isAbout"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="&bfo;BFO_0000015"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</rdfs:subClassOf>
		<rdfs:label>impact information content entity</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>an impact information content entity stating that variation in manganese concentration in cell culture medium impacts variation in galactosylation profile during a fed-batch cell culture process; an impact information content entity stating that variation in feed start time impacts variation in product glycosylation profile during a cell culture process; an impact information content entity stating that variation in agitation rate impacts variation in gas transfer rate during a gas-fermentation process; an impact information content entity stating that variation in low-pH hold duration impacts variation in viral clearance during a viral inactivation process;</skos:example>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>1) An attribute impact information content entity is an evidence-supported interpretation, not merely a correlation result. It may be supported by process data, correlation analysis, designed experiments, mechanistic knowledge, deviation investigations, SME assessment, or a combination of these.
2) The impact source and impact target relations specify directionality. The impact source is the specifically dependent continuant, process characteristic, process profile, or temporal region whose variation, value, or occurrence is characterized as influencing the variation, value, or occurrence of the impact target.
3) The impact source or impact target may be a specifically dependent continuant, process characteristic, process profile, or temporal region. Temporal regions are allowed when the impact concerns timing, duration, residence time, hold time, or another temporally specified aspect of a process. For example, an attribute impact description may specify the temporal region corresponding to feed start time as the impact source and glycosylation profile as the impact target.  
4) An attribute impact information content entity should be grounded in the process context where the impact occurs. For most impact claims, the source and target are attributes, process characteristics, or process profiles. In these cases, the physical basis of the impact can often be represented using material state transitions. The impact claim is not merely that one transition happened before another in a particular run. Rather, it characterizes a process-scoped relationship in which transitions associated with the impact source are understood, under the specified conditions, to cause transitions associated with the impact target. Temporal regions are a special case. A time point or duration is not itself the physical cause of an impact. Instead, it identifies when a relevant process part occurs or how long it lasts. For example, if feed start time is described as impacting glycosylation profile, the physical basis is not the time point itself. The impact is grounded in the feed addition process that starts at that time and in how that process changes the conditions for downstream cell culture and glycosylation-related material state transitions</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="&xsd;boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>information content entity that describes an influence of variation in an impact source on variation in an impact target during a specified kind of process</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
		<iof-av:primitiveRationale>There are insufficient constructs to create necessary and sufficient conditions.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;MathematicalFunction">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;InformationContentEntity"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">mathematical function</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>a rule that returns x² if x ≥ 0 and –x otherwise; a rule that outputs 0 when the input is below a threshold and 1 when it is above; temperature-conversion function that takes a value in degrees Celsius and returns the corresponding value in degrees Fahrenheit; f(x) = 2x + 1 maps each number x to a value twice as large plus one; any polynomial function</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>http://purl.allotrope.org/ontologies/result#AFR_0001257 and https://www.britannica.com/science/function-mathematics</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:counterExample>a computer procedure that returns multiple unrelated outputs (e.g., a function that returns both a number and a plot object); a rule that yields different results for the same input depending on random seed or system state; computer function that writes data to a file or displays a message on the screen</iof-av:counterExample>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>This term refers to an information description that defines how each input value is associated with one or more outputs according to a defined expression or rule. The ‘expression or rule’ part covers both mathematical formulas and conditional statements. The ‘input set (domain)’ represents all allowed input values, and the ‘output set (codomain)’ represents the possible outcomes. In a strictly mathematical sense, each input corresponds to a single output, but in practical models this mapping may represent a range or distribution of values.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>MathematicalFunction(x) → InformationContentEntity(x)</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
		<iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="&xsd;boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">information content entity that is an expression or rule defining a mapping from each element of a specified input set (the domain) to an element of an output set (the codomain)</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
		<iof-av:primitiveRationale>There are insufficient constructs to create a set of necessary and sufficient conditions.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
		<iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>if x is an &apos;mathematical function&apos; then x is a &apos;information content entity&apos;</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;OutlierDetection">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&bfo;OBI_0200000"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">outlier detection</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Detection of outlier values in a bioreactor pH time series using predefined control limits; Identification of outlying assay replicate results before calculating the reported mean value; Detection of unusual product concentration measurements in a batch dataset using an interquartile range criterion; Identification of atypical raw material impurity values across supplier lots using a predefined outlier detection rule.</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/outlier-detection#:~:text=Outlier%20detection%20is%20defined%20as,fraud%20detection%20and%20data%20cleaning.&amp;text=How%20useful%20is%20this%20definition?</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>Outlier detection involves finding and isolating data points that deviate substantially from the typical patterns within a dataset, often referred to as anomalies or exceptions. This class is intended to cover a broader range of outlier detection approaches than those currently represented in STATO, including both hypothesis-based statistical tests and non-hypothesis or algorithmic methods for identifying outliers.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>DataTransformation(x) ∧ ∃y (achievesPlannedObjective(x, y) ∧ OutlierDetectionTestingObjective(y)) → OutlierDetection(x)</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
		<iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="&xsd;boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">data transformation process in which a data item is evaluated for the presence of outliers according to a detection criterion</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
		<iof-av:primitiveRationale>There are insufficient constructs to create a set of necessary and sufficient conditions.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
		<iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>if x is a &apos;data transformation&apos; and x &apos;achieves planned objective&apos; some &apos;outlier detection testing objective&apos; then x is an &apos;outlier detection&apos;</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:Class rdf:about="&iof-construct;ResponseSurfacePlot">
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&bfo;IAO_0000308"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">response surface plot</rdfs:label>
		<skos:example>Three-dimensional plot showing predicted enzyme yield as a function of pH and temperature.</skos:example>
		<iof-av:adaptedFrom>https://www.jmp.com/en/statistics-knowledge-portal/design-of-experiments/response-surface-methodology#:~:text=Response%20surface%20methodology%20(RSM)%20is,response%20across%20the%20experimental%20region. and https://wolfson.huji.ac.il/purification/PDF/Others/GE_DOE_in_Protein_Production_and_Purification_Handbook.pdf</iof-av:adaptedFrom>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>A response surface plot is typically constructed from the predictions of a fitted regression model, most often a second-order (quadratic) polynomial, derived from data obtained in a designed experiment such as a central composite or Box–Behnken design.
The figure illustrates how the predicted value of the dependent variable changes as the independent variables vary and may be presented as either a three-dimensional surface or a two-dimensional contour projection.
Such plots facilitate the interpretation of main, interaction, and curvature effects and assist in locating regions of optimal or critical response.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>ResponseSurfacePlot(x) → Figure(x)</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
		<iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="&xsd;boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">figure that depicts the predicted values of a dependent variable as a continuous surface over two or more independent variables</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
		<iof-av:primitiveRationale>There are insufficient constructs to create a set of necessary and sufficient conditions.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
		<iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>if x is an &apos;response surface plot&apos; then x is a &apos;figure&apos;</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
	</owl:Class>
	
	<owl:ObjectProperty rdf:about="&iof-construct;containsValuesForVariable">
		<rdfs:subPropertyOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;isAbout"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">contains values for variable</rdfs:label>
		<rdfs:domain rdf:resource="&bfo;IAO_0000100"/>
		<rdfs:range rdf:resource="&bfo;STATO_0000258"/>
		<skos:example>time-series dataset used in parameter fitting that holds pH measurements for the covariate variable denoting pH; design matrix providing the coded temperature levels (–1, 1) for twelve experimental runs of the temperature factor variable; regression dataset providing z-score-normalized substrate concentration values for an independent variable; single-run dataset recording the product titer value (measured or predicted) for the dependent variable representing product yield</skos:example>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>This relation applies to datasets containing one or many values, such as a single measured value, a column in a table, or an entire vector used in statistical or model-fitting analysis. The values in the dataset may be raw, coded (e.g., factor levels), or normalized  and each value represents the state of that variable in a specific experimental run or model evaluation.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">relation that links a dataset to the variable whose values it holds</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:ObjectProperty>
	
	<owl:ObjectProperty rdf:about="&iof-construct;quantifiesStatisticalAssociationOf">
		<rdfs:subPropertyOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;describes"/>
		<rdfs:label xml:lang="en-US">quantifies statistical association of</rdfs:label>
		<rdfs:domain rdf:resource="&bfo;STATO_0000610"/>
		<rdfs:range rdf:resource="&bfo;IAO_0000027"/>
		<skos:example>correlation coefficient relating temperature and growth rate; mutual information value linking transcriptomic and proteomic datasets</skos:example>
		<iof-av:explanatoryNote>The property identifies the data items whose statistical relationship is characterized by a quantitative measure of association (e.g., correlation coefficient, mutual information, or association coefficient). The measure reifies the association; one assertion is made per participating data item. No causal or directional interpretation is implied.</iof-av:explanatoryNote>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en-US">relation that links a measure of association to each data item whose statistical relationship is described by that measure</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:ObjectProperty>
	
	<owl:ObjectProperty rdf:about="&iof-construct;specifiesImpactSource">
		<rdfs:subPropertyOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;describes"/>
		<rdfs:label>specifies impact source</rdfs:label>
		<rdfs:domain rdf:resource="&iof-construct;ImpactInformationContentEntity"/>
		<skos:example>an impact information content entity stating that manganese concentration impacts galactosylation profile specifies impact source the manganese concentration of the cell culture medium; an impact information content entity stating that feed start time impacts glycosylation profile specifies impact source the temporal region corresponding to feed start time;</skos:example>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>relation that holds between an impact information content entity and the entity specified as the source of the described impact</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:ObjectProperty>
	
	<owl:ObjectProperty rdf:about="&iof-construct;specifiesImpactTarget">
		<rdfs:subPropertyOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;describes"/>
		<rdfs:label>specifies impact target</rdfs:label>
		<rdfs:domain rdf:resource="&iof-construct;ImpactInformationContentEntity"/>
		<skos:example>an impact information content entity stating that manganese concentration impacts galactosylation profile specifies impact target the galactosylation profile of the produced glycoprotein population;</skos:example>
		<iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>relation that holds between an impact information content entity and the entity specified as the target of the described impact</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
	</owl:ObjectProperty>
	
	<owl:Class>
		<rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="&iof-construct;OutlierDetection"/>
		<owl:intersectionOf rdf:parseType="Collection">
			<rdf:Description rdf:about="&bfo;OBI_0200000">
			</rdf:Description>
			<owl:Restriction>
				<owl:onProperty rdf:resource="&bfo;OBI_0000417"/>
				<owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="&bfo;STATO_0000439"/>
			</owl:Restriction>
		</owl:intersectionOf>
	</owl:Class>
</rdf:RDF>